dspace-development.title: Update the oaworkflow-dev and oaworkflow X.509 certificates

comments.body:
The following error keeps arising for the Windows Server environments, and I am searching for any potential solutions for this:

![image.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5b5b6aed981c3204c9ed06c8/46e7b962-eba5-4ba2-8588-e87971cf15f6)

I am afraid that I am going to need to proceed with just attempting to request support from the OIT with this, as no alternative solutions which I have been attempting seem to be effective, and the X.509 certificate itself seems to be valid:

```bash
openssl pkcs12 -info -in ./oaworkflow_princeton_edu_11_11_2022.pfx
Enter Import Password:
MAC: sha256, Iteration 2048
MAC length: 32, salt length: 8
PKCS7 Encrypted data: PBES2, PBKDF2, AES-256-CBC, Iteration 2048, PRF hmacWithSHA256
Certificate bag
Bag Attributes
    localKeyID: 08 61 DB C7 88 F9 64 3C DC 4A 83 09 3E A4 0D B2 23 18 3D F0
subject=C = US, ST = New Jersey, O = The Trustees of Princeton University, OU = OIT, CN = oaworkflow.princeton.edu
issuer=C = US, ST = MI, L = Ann Arbor, O = Internet2, OU = InCommon, CN = InCommon RSA Server CA
-----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----
```

Using a series of wizard interactions, I seem to have imported the certificate without the conversion to PKCS#12:

![image.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5b5b6aed981c3204c9ed06c8/4c472070-c04a-4389-9371-45b41946de8c)

Unfortunately, this does not seem to be persisting, and I have proceeding with a SN@P request for support: https://princeton.service-now.com/service?id=ticket&table=incident&sys_id=556d569f87dc45d49cd197183cbb35e3&view=sp

After a troubleshooting session using Microsoft Teams, one of the Identity and Infrastructure Analysts within OIT has confirmed and documented that I seem to be properly generating the PKCS 12 binary for import into the IIS. They have been provided with a test PKCS binary, and they are investigating how they might be able to further assist by testing this using a separate IIS configuration.

Attempting to convert the PEM into the PKCS 12 format within the Windows Server requires that a version of `openssl` be installed. This, unfortunately, is not available:

![image.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5b5b6aed981c3204c9ed06c8/641a6cb3-d636-4dba-b267-c9910da358ba)
